September 26.

What does that mean?

More Brits make babies 38-weeks earlier on January 2 (between 10PM and 11:00PM GMT, with 10:36PM being the most amorous minute of the year) than at any other time of the year. So warm up the sheets, get out the lingerie and oils and get ready to do your patriot duty United Kingdom. Celebrate Baby Making Day the best way you can...canoodling for the future!",Statistical Event. No Sponsor. ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
Backwards Day: January 31,Worldwide,1,31,2021,1,31,2021,44,13,,,,,Daily,Same,,http://blog.hope-education.co.uk/early-years/classroom-ideas-celebrate-national-backwards-day/,,,About Backwards Day,,"Backwards Day is an organic celebration with no sponsor, celebrated worldwide. The basic concept of the day? Do everything in reverse.  Eat dessert first. Call people by their last name. Read a book back to front. Back into your parking space. See how many palindromes you can identify, (words spelled the same forward and back). You get the idea! 

Historically there is something called “Backwards Day,” but there is no specific reason for designating January 31 to observe it. 

The original Backwards Day occurred in the  Julian Calendar (45BC-1582), the predecessor of the modern Gregorian calendar. Day one of the Gregorian calendar is October 15, 1582, (though it would be the mid 1700s before it became the standard in Europe and the rest of the world).  

Because the Sun’s rotation around the earth is just shy of 365 days, the way the Roman’s dealt with this was to shift the calendar backwards one day every 128 years. With the rise of Christianity, this became a problem. Easter is determined by the vernal equinox and over the course of centuries, the Julian calendar caused the vernal equinox to move backwards by 10 days. 

The Gregorian calendar, with its leap year every four years, solved this problem. The Gregorian calendar also assured that the vernal equinox would always fall at the same time every year.","Unofficial Event. No Sponsor. See U.S. Department of Commerce, (NIST) for topical info.","National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST), Time and Frequency Division","325 Broadway, M/S 847",Boulder,CO,US,80305-3328,(303) 497.3295,michael.douma@idea.org.,"Michael Douma, Curator Calendars through the Ages",http://www.nist.gov/pml/div688/,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
