"Bootlegger's Day, Ntl.(1899/1920): January 17",United States,1,17,2021,1,17,2021,3,1,8,25,52,,Daily,Same,,https://www.templetonrye.com/history/,,,About National Bootlegger's Day,,"Bootleggers are smugglers, sometimes distillers, who bring in alcoholic beverages where they are either taxed or prohibited. National Bootlegger's Day marks two distinct anniversaries on January 17th. 

The birthday of bootlegger Al Capone: January 17, 1899
18th Amendment (Prohibition) goes into effect: January 17, 1920

The term 'bootlegger' refers to the flask smugglers used to hide in the top of their boots. In the age of the Old West, it was typically done to smuggle liquor to native Americans. With the advent of prohibition in the 1920s, it took on a whole new meaning.",Historical Anniversary.  No Sponsor.,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
"Braille Day, World (1809): January 4",Worldwide,1,4,2021,1,4,2021,3,13,20,,,,Daily,Same,,www.worldblindunion.org,,,About World Braille Day,,"Promoted by multiple organizations including the World Blind Union, World Braille Day celebrates the birth of Louis Braille on January 4, 1809. 

Braille was a Frenchman who lost his sight at a very early age. Braille learned to read using the Haüy system using Latin letters embossed on thick paper or leather. 

The Haüy system was difficult and didn’t allow for writing. Frustrated with it, Braille came up with a new code when he was only 15 years old. This system of dots in small rectangular blocks was far easier to read by touch. More importantly, it allowed for writing. 

Today Braille’s original code exists in several variations that accommodate different languages. His new language revolutionized communication for millions of people and opened up a world of learning, opportunity and independence.",Historical Event.  See the World Blind Union (WBU) for more information.,1929 Bayview Avenue,,Toronto,ON,CA,M4G3E8,(416) 486.9698,info@wbu.ngo,General Information,http://www.worldblindunion.org/English/contact-us/Pages/default.aspx,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
