Citizen United Decision by Supreme Court (2010): January 21,United States,1,21,2021,1,21,2021,3,36,18,25,52, ,Daily,Same, ,http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/citizens-united-v-federal-election-commission/,,,About the Anniversary of the Citizen United Decision  by Supreme Court in 2012,,"Today is the 10th anniversary of the landmark Citizens United decision, which was upheld by the US Supreme Court in 2010. 

The court stated, in 2010 that corporations, like people, have a constitutional right to be heard in election campaigns and that there should be no limit to the amount of money corporations and unions can spend in elections, as long as the money is independent of the campaign it intends to support.

This decision has flooded national and local elections in the United States with billions of dollars from special interests groups, creating an atmosphere of competing messages and non-transparent agenda funding.",Historical Anniversary. See the US Supreme Court,Supreme Court of the United States,"1 First Street, NE",Washington,DC,US,20543,(202) 479.3211  Reporters press 1, ,Media Relations,https://www.supremecourt.gov/contact/contactus.aspx,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
"Clam Chowder Day, New England Style: January 21*",United States,1,21,2021,1,21,2021,19,52,,,,,Daily,Same,,http://www.narragansettbeer.com/recipe/national-new-england-clam-chowder-day?age-verified=19e09aef05,,,About National New England Clam Chowder Day,,"This is one of two unofficial events celebrating clam chowder. The other is in February 25. Their are several varieties of clam chowder, the most common being  New England (white sauce), Manhattan (red sauce) and Rhode Island Clam Chowder (clear broth).

Chowder is a cross between a stew and a soup, essentially made of vegetables and fish stewed in a cauldron. Calderia is Latin for a “place for warming things.” Jowter is old English for a “fish peddler”. It is believed that this is the origin of the word chowder. The first recipes for chowder seem originate in both France and England, among the coastal fishing villages. The custom was to have a cauldron of simmering in the house, awaiting the fishing ships return to port. A portion of each man’s catch would be tossed in and the resulting chowder was served to the community to celebrate the safe return of the ship.

Clams were an easy choice, and could be gathered without the need to go out in a ship. This made them ideal for chowder, especially when the weather was bad. Of course clams could only be harvested at certain times of the year, so the chowder was often made from haddock, cod or other local fish. Chowder was a staple of the working classes.

Later recipes for chowder included other meats like ham, bacon and poultry. Clam chowder became a favorite with East Coast Americans, especially on Fridays due to a Christian custom of only eating fish on Friday.",Unofficial Event. No Sponsor. See the Maine Clammers Assoc. on topic. ,Maine Clammers Association ,PO Box 26,Freeport,ME,US,4032,(207) 615.5640,maineclammers@comcast.com,Media Relations,http://maineclammers.org/about/contact-us/,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,LEEP
